<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-225-206 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 383 433</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Feb 6 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Doubleday to publish Bill Gates biog. (biography of Microsoftfounder)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Endrijonas, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Officials and employees)Bantam Doubleday Dell Publishing Group Inc. (Planning).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Topic:     Software PublishersBiographyResearch and Development.andO;Person:    Gates, William H. (Addresses, essays, lectures).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>****DOUBLEDAY TO PUBLISH BILL GATES BIOG 02/06/91 NEW YORK, NEW YORK, U.S.A.,andO;1991 FEB 6 (NB) -- Bill Gates, the college dropout who has amassed a personalfortune by building Microsoft into the world's largest computer softwarecompany, is to be the subject of an independent investigative biography.andM;The book, entitled &quot;Billion Dollar Bill: Gates and Microsoft and How TheyGrew,&quot; is scheduled for hard cover release in 1992.andP;  Co- authors for theproject are Stephen Manes, a columnist with PC/Computing magazine and theauthor of more than thirty books as well as being a software designer; andPaul Andrews, a high-tech reporter for the Seattle Times who has his ownweekly column.andM;Announcing plans for the book, Manes commented: &quot;Bill Gates is the mostinfluential person in the computer business.andP;  Now he's aggressively promotinghis version of a rosy future that includes a much broader role for thecomputer -- and for his company.andP;  Our book will show where that vision comesfrom and how much it might affect the way we live.&quot;andM;In a published statement, co-author Andrews called Gates &quot;the Henry Ford ofthe computer industry.&quot; He noted that Gates has managed to survive andprosper while others have not, &quot;one of the great American success stories ofour generation&quot; which to date has not been told.andM;Manes told Newsbytes that both authors are based in Seattle and are in anideal position to conduct extensive original research for the book which theyanticipate will reach some 500 pages.andM;The authors may be contacted directly on Compuserve.andP;  In addition, Manes maybe reached on MCI Mail 278-4258 (278-4258@mcimail.com on Usenet linkedservices) and fax at 206-722-4105.andP;  The voice line for reaching Manes is206-722-3219 while Andrews' voice number is 206-782-5105.andM;(Janet Endrijonas/19910206)</TEXT></DOC>